  tags={['Rust', 'Bevy', 'ECS', 'Roguelike', 'Procedural Generation']}
>

  <!-- DEFAULT SLOT: ABOUT -->
  <h2>About the Project</h2>
  <p>
    bevy_rogue is a passion project and an excuse to go deep on Rust. The goal is a real-time
    roguelike with satisfying moment-to-moment movement, procedurally generated maps, and
    emergent combat — all built on top of Bevy's ECS architecture.
  </p>
  <p>
    Unlike turn-based roguelikes, everything runs in real time. Player movement uses
    <code>FixedUpdate</code> for consistent physics-independent ticks, and the map renderer
    is built on <code>bevy_ecs_tilemap</code> for efficient chunk-based rendering.
  </p>

  <h3>Features</h3>
  <p>
    Procedural map generation using BSP and cellular automata, a field-of-view system with
    fog of war, tile-based collision, and a component-driven entity system for actors, items,
    and environmental objects.
  </p>

  <!-- TECH SLOT -->
  <Fragment slot="tech">
    <p>
      The project is built entirely in Rust using Bevy 0.18. The ECS architecture keeps
      systems cleanly separated — map generation, FOV calculation, movement, and rendering
      are all independent systems that communicate through components and resources.
    </p>
    <p>
      Rendering uses <code>bevy_ecs_tilemap</code> for the tile layer and Bevy's built-in
      sprite system for entities. The FOV system implements a symmetric shadowcasting
      algorithm for accurate line-of-sight calculation.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <!-- LEARNED SLOT -->
  <Fragment slot="learned">
    <p>
      Working in Rust has been a genuinely different experience from C++ or GDScript. The
      borrow checker forces you to think carefully about ownership in a way that naturally
      leads to cleaner ECS design — you can't easily share mutable state, which pushes
      you toward the component-driven patterns Bevy wants anyway.
    </p>
    <p>
      Bevy's ECS is powerful but opinionated. Understanding when to use events vs resources
      vs components for communication between systems took time, but the resulting
      architecture is very clean and easy to extend.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

</ProjectLayout>
